protein (VLDL)","High-density lipoprotein (HDL)","Intermediate-density lipoprotein (IDL)","Chylomicrons"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the liver, triglycerides are formed by the combination of three free fatty acids and glycerol, they are then packaged into \u003Cstrong\u003Every low-density lipoproteins (VLDL)\u003C/strong\u003E. VLDL is the primary lipoprotein complex responsible for transporting triglycerides from the liver to peripheral tissues. This process is crucial for distributing energy and maintaining lipid balance in the body.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow-density lipoprotein (LDL)\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily involved in the transport of cholesterol to tissues and is not the main carrier of triglycerides from the liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-density lipoprotein (HDL)\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in reverse cholesterol transport, carrying cholesterol from tissues back to the liver, and does not primarily transport triglycerides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntermediate-density lipoprotein (IDL)\u003C/strong\u003E is a transitional form between VLDL and LDL, and while it can carry triglycerides, it is not the primary complex for their transport from the liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChylomicrons\u003C/strong\u003E are responsible for transporting dietary triglycerides from the intestines to other parts of the body, not from the liver.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Free fatty acids are converted to triglycerides in the liver and are primarily incorporated into very low-density lipoproteins (VLDL).","VLDL is responsible for transporting triglycerides from the liver to peripheral tissues.","The conversion of triglycerides into VLDL is a key step in lipid metabolism."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: PMC8411952","Wakil SJ, Abu-Elheiga LA. Fatty acid metabolism: target for metabolic syndrome. J Lipid Res. 2009 Apr;50 Suppl(Suppl):S138-43. doi: 10.1194/jlr.R800079-JLR200. Epub 2008 Dec 1. PMID: 19047759; PMCID: PMC2674721"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97346"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17872"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97346"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T12:31:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T12:31:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10586"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115343"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"headi